+## Nemesis Pass 1 — First-Principles Trust Boundary Challenge
+
+### N1 — The daemon HTTP API is an unauthenticated control surface
+
+The daemon accepts any HTTP request without authentication, origin checking, or
+rate limiting. The architecture doc (line 237) correctly documents this as
+intentional for milestone 1. However:
+
+- When the operator follows the quickstart and sets `ZEND_BIND_HOST=0.0.0.0`,
+  any device on the LAN can POST `/miner/start`, `/miner/stop`, or
+  `/miner/set_mode` without any credential.
+- The capability model (`observe`/`control`) exists only at the CLI layer. The
+  HTML client and any direct HTTP caller bypass it entirely.
+- A compromised or malicious device on the LAN has full miner control authority.
+- JavaScript running in any browser tab on the same machine can call the daemon
+  API (localhost).
+
+**Assessment:** Acceptable for milestone 1 with LAN-only default binding, but
+the operator quickstart should include an explicit threat model paragraph: "Any
+device that can reach port 8080 has full control of the miner. The capability
+model is enforced only by the CLI and scripts, not by the daemon itself."
+
+### N2 — Pairing store is a plaintext trust anchor with no integrity protection
+
+`state/pairing-store.json` is the sole authority for which devices have which
+capabilities. It is a plaintext JSON file writable by any process running as the
+daemon user. There is no MAC, signature, or integrity check. An attacker with
+filesystem write access can escalate an `observe`-only device to `control` by
+editing the JSON.
+
+**Assessment:** Acceptable for milestone 1 (LAN-only, single-user home
+hardware). The operator quickstart's hardening checklist (line 275) correctly
+recommends `chmod 700 state/`. No doc change needed, but this should be flagged
+for milestone 2 design.
+
+### N3 — Token expiry is declared but never enforced
+
+`GatewayPairing.token_expires_at` is set during pairing but never checked on any
+code path. `ZEND_TOKEN_TTL_HOURS` is documented but not read by the code. An
+operator reading the docs may believe tokens expire after 24 hours. They do not.
+
+**Assessment:** The operator quickstart says "not yet enforced" (line 61) — that
+parenthetical is doing important work but is easy to miss. Recommend making this
+more prominent: a dedicated callout box or warning, not a parenthetical.
+
+### N4 — PID file can be stale after daemon crash
+
+`state/daemon.pid` is written on daemon start. If the daemon crashes (SIGKILL,
+OOM, power loss), the PID file persists and may reference a dead or reused PID.
+`bootstrap_home_miner.sh` appears to handle this, but a stale PID could cause
+the script to kill an unrelated process if the PID was reused by the OS.
+
+**Assessment:** Low severity for a home device. The bootstrap script should check
+if the PID's process is actually a Python/Zend process before sending SIGTERM.
+
